</tr><tr><td class="sidebar-navbar"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1129693374"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1063604349">.mw-parser-output .navbar{display:inline;font-size:88%;font-weight:normal}.mw-parser-output .navbar-collapse{float:left;text-align:left}.mw-parser-output .navbar-boxtext{word-spacing:0}.mw-parser-output .navbar ul{display:inline-block;white-space:nowrap;line-height:inherit}.mw-parser-output .navbar-brackets::before{margin-right:-0.125em;content:"[ "}.mw-parser-output .navbar-brackets::after{margin-left:-0.125em;content:" ]"}.mw-parser-output .navbar li{word-spacing:-0.125em}.mw-parser-output .navbar a>span,.mw-parser-output .navbar a>abbr{text-decoration:inherit}.mw-parser-output .navbar-mini abbr{font-variant:small-caps;border-bottom:none;text-decoration:none;cursor:inherit}.mw-parser-output .navbar-ct-full{font-size:114%;margin:0 7em}.mw-parser-output .navbar-ct-mini{font-size:114%;margin:0 4em}</style><div class="navbar plainlinks hlist navbar-mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Machine_learning" title="Template:Machine learning"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Machine_learning" title="Template talk:Machine learning"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a href="/wiki/Special:EditPage/Template:Machine_learning" title="Special:EditPage/Template:Machine learning"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Data mining</b> is the process of extracting and discovering patterns in large <a href="/wiki/Data_set" title="Data set">data sets</a> involving methods at the intersection of <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a>, <a href="/wiki/Statistics" title="Statistics">statistics</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Database_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Database system">database systems</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-acm_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-acm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Data mining is an <a href="/wiki/Interdisciplinary" class="mw-redirect" title="Interdisciplinary">interdisciplinary</a> subfield of <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer science</a> and <a href="/wiki/Statistics" title="Statistics">statistics</a> with an overall goal of extracting information (with intelligent methods) from a data set and transforming the information into a comprehensible structure for further use.<sup id="cite_ref-acm_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-acm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-brittanica_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-brittanica-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-elements_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-elements-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Data mining is the analysis step of the "<a href="/wiki/Knowledge_discovery" class="mw-redirect" title="Knowledge discovery">knowledge discovery in databases</a>" process, or KDD.<sup id="cite_ref-Fayyad_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fayyad-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Aside from the raw analysis step, it also involves database and <a href="/wiki/Data_management" title="Data management">data management</a> aspects, <a href="/wiki/Data_pre-processing" class="mw-redirect" title="Data pre-processing">data pre-processing</a>, <a href="/wiki/Statistical_model" title="Statistical model">model</a> and <a href="/wiki/Statistical_inference" title="Statistical inference">inference</a> considerations, interestingness metrics, <a href="/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" title="Computational complexity theory">complexity</a> considerations, post-processing of discovered structures, <a href="/wiki/Data_and_information_visualization" title="Data and information visualization">visualization</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Online_algorithm" title="Online algorithm">online updating</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-acm_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-acm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The term "data mining" is a <a href="/wiki/Misnomer" title="Misnomer">misnomer</a> because the goal is the extraction of <a href="/wiki/Pattern" title="Pattern">patterns</a> and knowledge from large amounts of data, not the <a href="/wiki/Data_scraping" title="Data scraping">extraction (<i>mining</i>) of data itself</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-han-kamber_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-han-kamber-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> It also is a <a href="/wiki/Buzzword" title="Buzzword">buzzword</a><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> and is frequently applied to any form of large-scale data or <a href="/wiki/Data_processing" title="Data processing">information processing</a> (<a href="/wiki/Data_collection" title="Data collection">collection</a>, <a href="/wiki/Information_extraction" title="Information extraction">extraction</a>, <a href="/wiki/Data_warehouse" title="Data warehouse">warehousing</a>, analysis, and statistics) as well as any application of <a href="/wiki/Decision_support_system" title="Decision support system">computer decision support system</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligence</a> (e.g., machine learning) and <a href="/wiki/Business_intelligence" title="Business intelligence">business intelligence</a>. Often the more general terms (<i>large scale</i>) <i><a href="/wiki/Data_analysis" title="Data analysis">data analysis</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Analytics" title="Analytics">analytics</a></i>—or, when referring to actual methods, <i>artificial intelligence</i> and <i>machine learning</i>—are more appropriate.
</p><p>The actual data mining task is the semi-<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/automatic" class="extiw" title="wikt:automatic">automatic</a> or automatic analysis of large quantities of data to extract previously unknown, interesting patterns such as groups of data records (<a href="/wiki/Cluster_analysis" title="Cluster analysis">cluster analysis</a>), unusual records (<a href="/wiki/Anomaly_detection" title="Anomaly detection">anomaly detection</a>), and <a href="/wiki/Dependency_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Dependency (computer science)">dependencies</a> (<a href="/wiki/Association_rule_mining" class="mw-redirect" title="Association rule mining">association rule mining</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sequential_pattern_mining" title="Sequential pattern mining">sequential pattern mining</a>). This usually involves using database techniques such as <a href="/wiki/Spatial_index" class="mw-redirect" title="Spatial index">spatial indices</a>. These patterns can then be seen as a kind of summary of the input data, and may be used in further analysis or, for example, in machine learning and <a href="/wiki/Predictive_analytics" title="Predictive analytics">predictive analytics</a>. For example, the data mining step might identify multiple groups in the data, which can then be used to obtain more accurate prediction results by a <a href="/wiki/Decision_support_system" title="Decision support system">decision support system</a>. Neither the data collection, data preparation, nor result interpretation and reporting is part of the data mining step, although they do belong to the overall KDD process as additional steps.
</p><p>The difference between <a href="/wiki/Data_analysis" title="Data analysis">data analysis</a> and data mining is that data analysis is used to test models and hypotheses on the dataset, e.g., analyzing the effectiveness of a <a href="/wiki/Marketing_campaign" class="mw-redirect" title="Marketing campaign">marketing campaign</a>, regardless of the amount of data. In contrast, data mining uses machine learning and statistical models to uncover clandestine or hidden patterns in a large volume of data.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The related terms <i><a href="/wiki/Data_dredging" title="Data dredging">data dredging</a></i>, <i>data fishing</i>, and <i><a href="/wiki/Data_snooping" class="mw-redirect" title="Data snooping">data snooping</a></i> refer to the use of data mining methods to sample parts of a larger population data set that are (or may be) too small for reliable statistical inferences to be made about the validity of any patterns discovered. These methods can, however, be used in creating new hypotheses to test against the larger data populations.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Etymology">Etymology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In the 1960s, statisticians and economists used terms like <i>data fishing</i> or <i>data dredging</i> to refer to what they considered the bad practice of analyzing data without an <a href="/wiki/A_priori_probability" class="mw-redirect" title="A priori probability">a-priori</a> hypothesis. The term "data mining" was used in a similarly critical way by economist <a href="/wiki/Michael_Lovell" title="Michael Lovell">Michael Lovell</a> in an article published in the <i><a href="/wiki/Review_of_Economic_Studies" class="mw-redirect" title="Review of Economic Studies">Review of Economic Studies</a></i> in 1983.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Lovell indicates that the practice "masquerades under a variety of aliases, ranging from "experimentation" (positive) to "fishing" or "snooping" (negative).
</p><p>The term <i>data mining</i> appeared around 1990 in the database community, with generally positive connotations. For a short time in 1980s, the phrase "database mining"™, was used, but since it was trademarked by HNC, a <a href="/wiki/San_Diego" title="San Diego">San Diego</a>-based company, to pitch their Database Mining Workstation;<sup id="cite_ref-Mena_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Mena-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> researchers consequently turned to <i>data mining</i>. Other terms used include <i>data archaeology</i>, <i>information harvesting</i>, <i>information discovery</i>, <i><a href="/wiki/Knowledge_extraction" title="Knowledge extraction">knowledge extraction</a></i>, etc. <a href="/wiki/Gregory_I._Piatetsky-Shapiro" class="mw-redirect" title="Gregory I. Piatetsky-Shapiro">Gregory Piatetsky-Shapiro</a> coined the term "knowledge discovery in databases" for the first workshop on the same topic <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.kdnuggets.com/meetings/kdd89/">(KDD-1989)</a> and this term became more popular in the <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title="Artificial intelligence">AI</a> and <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a> communities. However, the term data mining became more popular in the business and press communities.<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Currently, the terms <i>data mining</i> and <i>knowledge discovery</i> are used interchangeably.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Background">Background</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Background"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The manual extraction of patterns from <a href="/wiki/Data" title="Data">data</a> has occurred for centuries. Early methods of identifying patterns in data include <a href="/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem" title="Bayes&#39; theorem">Bayes' theorem</a> (1700s) and <a href="/wiki/Regression_analysis" title="Regression analysis">regression analysis</a> (1800s).<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The proliferation, ubiquity and increasing power of computer technology have dramatically increased data collection, storage, and manipulation ability. As <a href="/wiki/Data_set" title="Data set">data sets</a> have grown in size and complexity, direct "hands-on" data analysis has increasingly been augmented with indirect, automated data processing, aided by other discoveries in computer science, specially in the field of machine learning, such as <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Artificial neural network">neural networks</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cluster_analysis" title="Cluster analysis">cluster analysis</a>, <a href="/wiki/Genetic_algorithms" class="mw-redirect" title="Genetic algorithms">genetic algorithms</a> (1950s), <a href="/wiki/Decision_tree_learning" title="Decision tree learning">decision trees</a> and <a href="/wiki/Decision_rules" class="mw-redirect" title="Decision rules">decision rules</a> (1960s), and <a href="/wiki/Support_vector_machines" class="mw-redirect" title="Support vector machines">support vector machines</a> (1990s). Data mining is the process of applying these methods with the intention of uncovering hidden patterns.<sup id="cite_ref-Kantardzic_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kantardzic-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> in large data sets. It bridges the gap from <a href="/wiki/Applied_statistics" class="mw-redirect" title="Applied statistics">applied statistics</a> and artificial intelligence (which usually provide the mathematical background) to <a href="/wiki/Database_management" class="mw-redirect" title="Database management">database management</a> by exploiting the way data is stored and indexed in databases to execute the actual learning and discovery algorithms more efficiently, allowing such methods to be applied to ever-larger data sets.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Process">Process</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Process"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The <i>knowledge discovery in databases (KDD) process</i> is commonly defined with the stages:
</p>
<ol><li>Selection</li>
<li>Pre-processing</li>
<li>Transformation</li>
<li><i>Data mining</i></li>
<li>Interpretation/evaluation.<sup id="cite_ref-Fayyad_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fayyad-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></li></ol>
<p>It exists, however, in many variations on this theme, such as the <a href="/wiki/Cross-industry_standard_process_for_data_mining" title="Cross-industry standard process for data mining">Cross-industry standard process for data mining</a> (CRISP-DM) which defines six phases:
</p>
<ol><li>Business understanding</li>
<li>Data understanding</li>
<li>Data preparation</li>
<li>Modeling</li>
<li>Evaluation</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/System_deployment" title="System deployment">Deployment</a></li></ol>
<p>or a simplified process such as (1) Pre-processing, (2) Data Mining, and (3) Results Validation.
</p><p>Polls conducted in 2002, 2004, 2007 and 2014 show that the CRISP-DM methodology is the leading methodology used by data miners.<sup id="cite_ref-KDN_1_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KDN_1-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-KDN_2_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KDN_2-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-KDN_3_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KDN_3-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-KDN_4_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KDN_4-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The only other data mining standard named in these polls was <a href="/wiki/SEMMA" title="SEMMA">SEMMA</a>. However, 3–4 times as many people reported using CRISP-DM. Several teams of researchers have published reviews of data mining process models,<sup id="cite_ref-kurgan_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kurgan-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> and Azevedo and Santos conducted a comparison of CRISP-DM and SEMMA in 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-AzevedoSantos_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AzevedoSantos-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Pre-processing">Pre-processing</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Pre-processing"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Before data mining algorithms can be used, a target data set must be assembled. As data mining can only uncover patterns actually present in the data, the target data set must be large enough to contain these patterns while remaining concise enough to be mined within an acceptable time limit. A common source for data is a <a href="/wiki/Data_mart" title="Data mart">data mart</a> or <a href="/wiki/Data_warehouse" title="Data warehouse">data warehouse</a>. Pre-processing is essential to analyze the <a href="/wiki/Multivariate_statistics" title="Multivariate statistics">multivariate</a> data sets before data mining. The target set is then cleaned. Data cleaning removes the observations containing <a href="/wiki/Statistical_noise" class="mw-redirect" title="Statistical noise">noise</a> and those with <a href="/wiki/Missing_data" title="Missing data">missing data</a>.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Data_mining">Data mining</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Data mining"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Data mining involves six common classes of tasks:<sup id="cite_ref-Fayyad_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fayyad-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Anomaly_detection" title="Anomaly detection">Anomaly detection</a> (outlier/change/deviation detection) – The identification of unusual data records, that might be interesting or data errors that require further investigation due to being out of standard range.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Association_rule_learning" title="Association rule learning">Association rule learning</a> (dependency modeling) – Searches for relationships between variables. For example, a supermarket might gather data on customer purchasing habits. Using association rule learning, the supermarket can determine which products are frequently bought together and use this information for marketing purposes. This is sometimes referred to as market basket analysis.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cluster_analysis" title="Cluster analysis">Clustering</a> – is the task of discovering groups and structures in the data that are in some way or another "similar", without using known structures in the data.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Statistical_classification" title="Statistical classification">Classification</a> – is the task of generalizing known structure to apply to new data. For example, an e-mail program might attempt to classify an e-mail as "legitimate" or as "spam".</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Regression_analysis" title="Regression analysis">Regression</a> – attempts to find a function that models the data with the least error that is, for estimating the relationships among data or datasets.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Automatic_summarization" title="Automatic summarization">Summarization</a> – providing a more compact representation of the data set, including visualization and report generation.</li></ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Results_validation">Results validation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Results validation"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg/390px-Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg.png" decoding="async" width="390" height="154" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg/585px-Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg/780px-Spurious_correlations_-_spelling_bee_spiders.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1040" data-file-height="410" /></a><figcaption>An example of data produced by <a href="/wiki/Data_dredging" title="Data dredging">data dredging</a> through a bot operated by statistician Tyler Vigen, apparently showing a close link between the best word winning a spelling bee competition and the number of people in the United States killed by venomous spiders</figcaption></figure><p>Data mining can unintentionally be misused, producing results that appear to be significant but which do not actually predict future behavior and cannot be <a href="/wiki/Reproducibility" title="Reproducibility">reproduced</a> on a new sample of data, therefore bearing little use. This is sometimes caused by investigating too many hypotheses and not performing proper <a href="/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class="mw-redirect" title="Statistical hypothesis testing">statistical hypothesis testing</a>. A simple version of this problem in <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a> is known as <a href="/wiki/Overfitting" title="Overfitting">overfitting</a>, but the same problem can arise at different phases of the process and thus a train/test split—when applicable at all—may not be sufficient to prevent this from happening.<sup id="cite_ref-hawkins_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hawkins-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The final step of knowledge discovery from data is to verify that the patterns produced by the data mining algorithms occur in the wider data set. Not all patterns found by the algorithms are necessarily valid. It is common for data mining algorithms to find patterns in the training set which are not present in the general data set. This is called <a href="/wiki/Overfitting" title="Overfitting">overfitting</a>. To overcome this, the evaluation uses a <a href="/wiki/Test_set" class="mw-redirect" title="Test set">test set</a> of data on which the data mining algorithm was not trained. The learned patterns are applied to this test set, and the resulting output is compared to the desired output. For example, a data mining algorithm trying to distinguish "spam" from "legitimate" e-mails would be trained on a <a href="/wiki/Training_set" class="mw-redirect" title="Training set">training set</a> of sample e-mails. Once trained, the learned patterns would be applied to the test set of e-mails on which it had <i>not</i> been trained. The accuracy of the patterns can then be measured from how many e-mails they correctly classify. Several statistical methods may be used to evaluate the algorithm, such as <a href="/wiki/Receiver_operating_characteristic" title="Receiver operating characteristic">ROC curves</a>.
</p><p>If the learned patterns do not meet the desired standards, it is necessary to re-evaluate and change the pre-processing and data mining steps. If the learned patterns do meet the desired standards, then the final step is to interpret the learned patterns and turn them into knowledge.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Research">Research</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Research"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The premier professional body in the field is the <a href="/wiki/Association_for_Computing_Machinery" title="Association for Computing Machinery">Association for Computing Machinery</a>'s (ACM) Special Interest Group (SIG) on Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining (<a href="/wiki/SIGKDD" class="mw-redirect" title="SIGKDD">SIGKDD</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> Since 1989, this ACM SIG has hosted an annual international conference and published its proceedings,<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> and since 1999 it has published a biannual <a href="/wiki/Academic_journal" title="Academic journal">academic journal</a> titled "SIGKDD Explorations".<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Computer science conferences on data mining include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/CIKM_Conference" class="mw-redirect" title="CIKM Conference">CIKM Conference</a> – ACM <a href="/wiki/Conference_on_Information_and_Knowledge_Management" title="Conference on Information and Knowledge Management">Conference on Information and Knowledge Management</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/European_Conference_on_Machine_Learning_and_Principles_and_Practice_of_Knowledge_Discovery_in_Databases" class="mw-redirect" title="European Conference on Machine Learning and Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases">European Conference on Machine Learning and Principles and Practice of Knowledge Discovery in Databases</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/KDD_Conference" class="mw-redirect" title="KDD Conference">KDD Conference</a> – ACM SIGKDD <a href="/wiki/Conference_on_Knowledge_Discovery_and_Data_Mining" class="mw-redirect" title="Conference on Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining">Conference on Knowledge Discovery and Data Mining</a></li></ul>
<p>Data mining topics are also present in many <a href="/wiki/List_of_computer_science_conferences#Data_Management" title="List of computer science conferences">data management/database conferences</a> such as the ICDE Conference, <a href="/wiki/SIGMOD" title="SIGMOD">SIGMOD Conference</a> and <a href="/wiki/International_Conference_on_Very_Large_Data_Bases" title="International Conference on Very Large Data Bases">International Conference on Very Large Data Bases</a>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Standards">Standards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Standards"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>There have been some efforts to define standards for the data mining process, for example, the 1999 European <a href="/wiki/Cross_Industry_Standard_Process_for_Data_Mining" class="mw-redirect" title="Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining">Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining</a> (CRISP-DM 1.0) and the 2004 <a href="/wiki/Java_Data_Mining" title="Java Data Mining">Java Data Mining</a> standard (JDM 1.0). Development on successors to these processes (CRISP-DM 2.0 and JDM 2.0) was active in 2006 but has stalled since. JDM 2.0 was withdrawn without reaching a final draft.
</p><p>For exchanging the extracted models—in particular for use in <a href="/wiki/Predictive_analytics" title="Predictive analytics">predictive analytics</a>—the key standard is the <a href="/wiki/Predictive_Model_Markup_Language" title="Predictive Model Markup Language">Predictive Model Markup Language</a> (PMML), which is an <a href="/wiki/XML" title="XML">XML</a>-based language developed by the Data Mining Group (DMG) and supported as exchange format by many data mining applications. As the name suggests, it only covers prediction models, a particular data mining task of high importance to business applications. However, extensions to cover (for example) <a href="/wiki/Subspace_clustering" class="mw-redirect" title="Subspace clustering">subspace clustering</a> have been proposed independently of the DMG.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notable_uses">Notable uses</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Notable uses"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Examples_of_data_mining" title="Examples of data mining">Examples of data mining</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable selfref">See also: <a href="/wiki/Category:Applied_data_mining" title="Category:Applied data mining">Category:Applied data mining</a></div>
<p>Data mining is used wherever there is digital data available. Notable <a href="/wiki/Examples_of_data_mining" title="Examples of data mining">examples of data mining</a> can be found throughout business, medicine, science, finance, construction, and surveillance.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Privacy_concerns_and_ethics">Privacy concerns and ethics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Privacy concerns and ethics"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>While the term "data mining" itself may have no ethical implications, it is often associated with the mining of information in relation to <a href="/wiki/User_behavior_analytics" title="User behavior analytics">user behavior</a> (ethical and otherwise).<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The ways in which data mining can be used can in some cases and contexts raise questions regarding <a href="/wiki/Privacy" title="Privacy">privacy</a>, legality, and <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> In particular, data mining government or commercial data sets for <a href="/wiki/National_security" title="National security">national security</a> or <a href="/wiki/Law_enforcement" title="Law enforcement">law enforcement</a> purposes, such as in the <a href="/wiki/Total_Information_Awareness" title="Total Information Awareness">Total Information Awareness</a> Program or in <a href="/wiki/ADVISE" title="ADVISE">ADVISE</a>, has raised privacy concerns.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Data mining requires data preparation which uncovers information or patterns which compromise <a href="/wiki/Confidentiality" title="Confidentiality">confidentiality</a> and <a href="/wiki/Data_privacy" class="mw-redirect" title="Data privacy">privacy</a> obligations. A common way for this to occur is through <a href="/wiki/Aggregate_function" title="Aggregate function">data aggregation</a>. <a href="/wiki/Data_aggregation" title="Data aggregation">Data aggregation</a> involves combining data together (possibly from various sources) in a way that facilitates analysis (but that also might make identification of private, individual-level data deducible or otherwise apparent).<sup id="cite_ref-NASCIO_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASCIO-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> This is not data mining <i>per se</i>, but a result of the preparation of data before—and for the purposes of—the analysis. The threat to an individual's privacy comes into play when the data, once compiled, cause the data miner, or anyone who has access to the newly compiled data set, to be able to identify specific individuals, especially when the data were originally anonymous.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>It is recommended<sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Words_to_watch#Unsupported_attributions" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Words to watch"><span title="The material near this tag may use weasel words or too-vague attribution. (August 2019)">according to whom?</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> to be aware of the following <b>before</b> data are collected:<sup id="cite_ref-NASCIO_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASCIO-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The purpose of the data collection and any (known) data mining projects.</li>
<li>How the data will be used.</li>
<li>Who will be able to mine the data and use the data and their derivatives.</li>
<li>The status of security surrounding access to the data.</li>
<li>How collected data can be updated.</li></ul>
<p>Data may also be modified so as to <i>become</i> anonymous, so that individuals may not readily be identified.<sup id="cite_ref-NASCIO_31-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASCIO-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> However, even "<a href="/wiki/Data_anonymization" title="Data anonymization">anonymized</a>" data sets can potentially contain enough information to allow identification of individuals, as occurred when journalists were able to find several individuals based on a set of search histories that were inadvertently released by AOL.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The inadvertent revelation of <a href="/wiki/Personally_identifiable_information" class="mw-redirect" title="Personally identifiable information">personally identifiable information</a> leading to the provider violates Fair Information Practices. This indiscretion can cause financial,
emotional, or bodily harm to the indicated individual. In one instance of <a href="/wiki/Privacy_violation" class="mw-redirect" title="Privacy violation">privacy violation</a>, the patrons of Walgreens filed a lawsuit against the company in 2011 for selling
prescription information to data mining companies who in turn provided the data
to pharmaceutical companies.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Situation_in_Europe">Situation in Europe</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Situation in Europe"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">Europe</a> has rather strong privacy laws, and efforts are underway to further strengthen the rights of the consumers. However, the <a href="/wiki/International_Safe_Harbor_Privacy_Principles" title="International Safe Harbor Privacy Principles">U.S.–E.U. Safe Harbor Principles</a>, developed between 1998 and 2000, currently effectively expose European users to privacy exploitation by U.S. companies. As a consequence of <a href="/wiki/Edward_Snowden" title="Edward Snowden">Edward Snowden</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Global_surveillance_disclosure" class="mw-redirect" title="Global surveillance disclosure">global surveillance disclosure</a>, there has been increased discussion to revoke this agreement, as in particular the data will be fully exposed to the <a href="/wiki/National_Security_Agency" title="National Security Agency">National Security Agency</a>, and attempts to reach an agreement with the United States have failed.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the United Kingdom in particular there have been cases of corporations using data mining as a way to target certain groups of customers forcing them to pay unfairly high prices. These groups tend to be people of lower socio-economic status who are not savvy to the ways they can be exploited in digital market places.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Situation_in_the_United_States">Situation in the United States</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Situation in the United States"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>In the United States, privacy concerns have been addressed by the <a href="/wiki/US_Congress" class="mw-redirect" title="US Congress">US Congress</a> via the passage of regulatory controls such as the <a href="/wiki/Health_Insurance_Portability_and_Accountability_Act" title="Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act">Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act</a> (HIPAA). The HIPAA requires individuals to give their "informed consent" regarding information they provide and its intended present and future uses. According to an article in <i>Biotech Business Week</i>, "'[i]n practice, HIPAA may not offer any greater protection than the longstanding regulations in the research arena,' says the AAHC. More importantly, the rule's goal of protection through informed consent is approach a level of incomprehensibility to average individuals."<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> This underscores the necessity for data anonymity in data aggregation and mining practices.
</p><p>U.S. information privacy legislation such as HIPAA and the <a href="/wiki/Family_Educational_Rights_and_Privacy_Act" title="Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act">Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act</a> (FERPA) applies only to the specific areas that each such law addresses. The use of data mining by the majority of businesses in the U.S. is not controlled by any legislation.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Copyright_law">Copyright law</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Copyright law"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Situation_in_Europe_2">Situation in Europe</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Situation in Europe"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Under <a href="/wiki/Copyright_law_of_the_European_Union" title="Copyright law of the European Union">European copyright</a> <a href="/wiki/Database_Directive" title="Database Directive">database laws</a>, the mining of in-copyright works (such as by <a href="/wiki/Web_mining" class="mw-redirect" title="Web mining">web mining</a>) without the permission of the copyright owner is not legal. Where a database is pure data in Europe, it may be that there is no copyright—but database rights may exist, so data mining becomes subject to <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" title="Intellectual property">intellectual property</a> owners' rights that are protected by the <a href="/wiki/Database_Directive" title="Database Directive">Database Directive</a>. On the recommendation of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Hargreaves_review&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Hargreaves review (page does not exist)">Hargreaves review</a>, this led to the UK government to amend its copyright law in 2014 to allow content mining as a <a href="/wiki/Limitations_and_exceptions_to_copyright" title="Limitations and exceptions to copyright">limitation and exception</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> The UK was the second country in the world to do so after Japan, which introduced an exception in 2009 for data mining. However, due to the restriction of the <a href="/wiki/Information_Society_Directive" class="mw-redirect" title="Information Society Directive">Information Society Directive</a> (2001), the UK exception only allows content mining for non-commercial purposes. UK copyright law also does not allow this provision to be overridden by contractual terms and conditions.
Since 2020 also Switzerland has been regulating data mining by allowing it in the research field under certain conditions laid down by art. 24d of the Swiss Copyright Act. This new article entered into force on 1 April 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/European_Commission" title="European Commission">European Commission</a> facilitated stakeholder discussion on text and data mining in 2013, under the title of Licences for Europe.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> The focus on the solution to this legal issue, such as licensing rather than limitations and exceptions, led to representatives of universities, researchers, libraries, civil society groups and <a href="/wiki/Open_access" title="Open access">open access</a> publishers to leave the stakeholder dialogue in May 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Situation_in_the_United_States_2">Situation in the United States</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Situation in the United States"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Copyright_law_of_the_United_States" title="Copyright law of the United States">US copyright law</a>, and in particular its provision for <a href="/wiki/Fair_use" title="Fair use">fair use</a>, upholds the legality of content mining in America, and other fair use countries such as Israel, Taiwan and South Korea. As content mining is transformative, that is it does not supplant the original work, it is viewed as being lawful under fair use. For example, as part of the <a href="/wiki/Google_Book_Search_Settlement_Agreement" class="mw-redirect" title="Google Book Search Settlement Agreement">Google Book settlement</a> the presiding judge on the case ruled that Google's digitization project of in-copyright books was lawful, in part because of the transformative uses that the digitization project displayed—one being text and data mining.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Software">Software</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Software"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable selfref">See also: <a href="/wiki/Category:Data_mining_and_machine_learning_software" title="Category:Data mining and machine learning software">Category:Data mining and machine learning software</a></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Free_open-source_data_mining_software_and_applications">Free open-source data mining software and applications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Free open-source data mining software and applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The following applications are available under free/open-source licenses. Public access to application source code is also available.
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Carrot2" title="Carrot2">Carrot2</a>: Text and search results clustering framework.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Chemicalize.org" class="mw-redirect" title="Chemicalize.org">Chemicalize.org</a>: A chemical structure miner and web search engine.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/ELKI" title="ELKI">ELKI</a>: A university research project with advanced <a href="/wiki/Cluster_analysis" title="Cluster analysis">cluster analysis</a> and <a href="/wiki/Anomaly_detection" title="Anomaly detection">outlier detection</a> methods written in the <a href="/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a> language.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/General_Architecture_for_Text_Engineering" title="General Architecture for Text Engineering">GATE</a>: a <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_processing" title="Natural language processing">natural language processing</a> and language engineering tool.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/KNIME" title="KNIME">KNIME</a>: The Konstanz Information Miner, a user-friendly and comprehensive data analytics framework.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/MOA_(Massive_Online_Analysis)" class="mw-redirect" title="MOA (Massive Online Analysis)">Massive Online Analysis (MOA)</a>: a real-time big data stream mining with concept drift tool in the <a href="/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a> programming language.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Multi_expression_programming" title="Multi expression programming">MEPX</a>: cross-platform tool for regression and classification problems based on a Genetic Programming variant.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mlpack" title="Mlpack">mlpack</a>: a collection of ready-to-use machine learning algorithms written in the <a href="/wiki/C%2B%2B" title="C++">C++</a> language.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/NLTK" class="mw-redirect" title="NLTK">NLTK</a> (<a href="/wiki/Natural_Language_Toolkit" title="Natural Language Toolkit">Natural Language Toolkit</a>): A suite of libraries and programs for symbolic and statistical natural language processing (NLP) for the <a href="/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title="Python (programming language)">Python</a> language.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/OpenNN" title="OpenNN">OpenNN</a>: Open <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Artificial neural network">neural networks</a> library.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orange_(software)" title="Orange (software)">Orange</a>: A component-based data mining and <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a> software suite written in the <a href="/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title="Python (programming language)">Python</a> language.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/PSPP" title="PSPP">PSPP</a>: Data mining and statistics software under the GNU Project similar to <a href="/wiki/SPSS" title="SPSS">SPSS</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/R_(programming_language)" title="R (programming language)">R</a>: A <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a> and software environment for <a href="/wiki/Statistics" title="Statistics">statistical</a> computing, data mining, and graphics. It is part of the <a href="/wiki/GNU_Project" title="GNU Project">GNU Project</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Scikit-learn" title="Scikit-learn">scikit-learn</a>: An open-source machine learning library for the Python programming language;</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Torch_(machine_learning)" title="Torch (machine learning)">Torch</a>: An <a href="/wiki/Open_source_model" class="mw-redirect" title="Open source model">open-source</a> <a href="/wiki/Deep_learning" title="Deep learning">deep learning</a> library for the <a href="/wiki/Lua_(programming_language)" title="Lua (programming language)">Lua</a> programming language and <a href="/wiki/Scientific_computing" class="mw-redirect" title="Scientific computing">scientific computing</a> framework with wide support for <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a> algorithms.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/UIMA" title="UIMA">UIMA</a>: The UIMA (Unstructured Information Management Architecture) is a component framework for analyzing unstructured content such as text, audio and video – originally developed by IBM.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Weka_(machine_learning)" class="mw-redirect" title="Weka (machine learning)">Weka</a>: A suite of machine learning software applications written in the <a href="/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a> programming language.</li></ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Proprietary_data-mining_software_and_applications">Proprietary data-mining software and applications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Data_mining&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Proprietary data-mining software and applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The following applications are available under proprietary licenses.
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Angoss" title="Angoss">Angoss</a> KnowledgeSTUDIO: data mining tool</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/LIONsolver" title="LIONsolver">LIONsolver</a>: an integrated software application for data mining, business intelligence, and modeling that implements the Learning and Intelligent OptimizatioN (LION) approach.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/PolyAnalyst" title="PolyAnalyst">PolyAnalyst</a>: data and text mining software by Megaputer Intelligence.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Analysis_Services" title="Microsoft Analysis Services">Microsoft Analysis Services</a>: data mining software provided by <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">Microsoft</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/NetOwl" title="NetOwl">NetOwl</a>: suite of multilingual text and entity analytics products that enable data mining.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oracle_Data_Mining" title="Oracle Data Mining">Oracle Data Mining</a>: data mining software by <a href="/wiki/Oracle_Corporation" title="Oracle Corporation">Oracle Corporation</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/PSeven" title="PSeven">PSeven</a>: platform for automation of engineering simulation and analysis, multidisciplinary optimization and data mining provided by <a href="/wiki/DATADVANCE" title="DATADVANCE">DATADVANCE</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Qlucore" title="Qlucore">Qlucore</a> Omics Explorer: data mining software.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/RapidMiner" title="RapidMiner">RapidMiner</a>: An environment for <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning</a> and data mining experiments.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/SAS_(software)#Components" title="SAS (software)">SAS Enterprise Miner</a>: data mining software provided by the <a href="/wiki/SAS_Institute" title="SAS Institute">SAS Institute</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/SPSS_Modeler" title="SPSS Modeler">SPSS Modeler</a>: data mining software provided by <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/STATISTICA" class="mw-redirect" title="STATISTICA">STATISTICA</a> Data Miner: data mining software provided by <a href="/wiki/StatSoft" title="StatSoft">StatSoft</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Tanagra_(machine_learning)" title="Tanagra (machine learning)">Tanagra</a>: Visualisation-oriented data mining software, also for teaching.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Vertica" title="Vertica">Vertica</a>: data mining software provided by <a href="/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" title="Hewlett-Packard">Hewlett-Packard</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Google_Cloud_Platform" title="Google Cloud Platform">Google Cloud Platform</a>: automated custom ML models managed by <a href="/wiki/Google" title="Google">Google</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Amazon_SageMaker" title="Amazon SageMaker">Amazon SageMaker</a>: managed service provided by <a href="/wiki/Amazon.com" class="mw-redirect" title="Amazon.com">Amazon</a> for creating &amp; productionising custom ML models.</li></ul>
